---
import Layout from "@components/Layout.astro";
import { confidenceDefinitions } from "@lib/confidence";
---

<Layout title="Methodology | Minneapolis Public Housing Explorer" description="How Minneapolis public housing records are compiled and categorized.">
  <section class="border-b border-line bg-paper">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-10 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold">Methodology</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-ink/75">
        This site compiles public records that identify or suggest Minneapolis public housing properties, then labels each record according to the strength of the available evidence.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-white">
    <div class="mx-auto grid max-w-4xl gap-8 px-4 py-8 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <article>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Sources Used</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-ink/70">
          Records are drawn from official or documented public sources, including HUD public housing building records, City of Minneapolis assessing records, Hennepin/MetroGIS parcel records, City of Minneapolis Construction and Code Services permit records, MPHA public portfolio information, and City of Minneapolis civic boundary layers.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">How Records Are Matched</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-ink/70">
          Parcel IDs, addresses, owner names, taxpayer names, property classifications, unit counts, and coordinates are standardized so records from different agencies can be compared. Each property keeps evidence notes that explain which public sources support the record.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Parcel Facts And Permits</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-ink/70">
          Parcel facts are condensed from the current MetroGIS open parcel layer and the latest Minneapolis assessing table into property-facts.csv and property-facts.json. Construction permits are landed as a full public source snapshot, then matched to exported properties by normalized parcel APN after extraction and published as property-permits.csv and property-permits.json. The public permit output includes permit numbers, type, status, value, issue and completion dates, unit changes, and work comments.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Civic Geography</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-ink/70">
          City limits, wards, neighborhoods, communities, police precincts, and MPD sectors are landed as separate boundary snapshots and published as civic-boundaries.geojson. Property points are spatially joined to those layers so the map, property detail pages, property search filters, and explorer summaries can use the same ward and neighborhood context.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Unit Count Basis</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-ink/70">
          Reported public-source unit counts are used first. When a count is missing, the pipeline applies conservative property-type or building-use inference, such as vacant land to 0 units or duplex to 2 units. Inferred counts are labeled with source, confidence, and notes so totals, assessed value per unit, and geography summaries can be reviewed with that context.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Privacy Boundary</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-ink/70">
          This site publishes property-level public-record context only. It does not collect or publish resident names, tenant records, household details, occupancy details tied to people, applicant contact fields, phone numbers, emails, or applicant addresses from permit records.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Confidence Rules</h2>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-3">
          {Object.entries(confidenceDefinitions).map(([, definition]) => (
            <div class="rounded border border-line bg-paper p-4">
              <h3 class="font-bold">{definition.label}</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-ink/70">{definition.description}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Known Limitations</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-ink/70">
          Public records can disagree, lag behind recent transactions, or describe ownership without directly identifying a specific MPHA program or building. Permit, parcel, boundary, and unit-count enrichment explains public context for a parcel, but it does not independently prove portfolio status. Inferred unit counts are best-effort public-record estimates, not occupancy or resident counts. Properties labeled likely should be reviewed against the cited sources before being treated as confirmed.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
